# New Orleans Creole Gumbo

> This updated Creole gumbo recipe uses Better Than Bouillon for a rich and savory base, focuses on shrimp for the seafood component, and adds file powder at service for freshness and texture. It's a flavorful and hearty dish perfect for capturing the essence of New Orleans cuisine. #seafood #creole #gumbo

- All-Purpose Flour | 1 cup | 
- Bacon Drippings | 3/4 cup | 

Whisk together flour and bacon drippings in a large, heavy saucepan over medium-low heat until smooth. Cook, whisking constantly, until it turns a rich mahogany brown color, about 20 to 30 minutes. Remove from heat; continue whisking until mixture stops cooking.

- Celery | 1 cup | 
- Onion | 1 large | 
- Green Bell Pepper | 1 large | 
- Garlic | 2 cloves | 

Pulse celery, onion, green bell pepper, and garlic in a food processor until very finely chopped.

- Andouille Sausage | 1 pound | 

Stir vegetables into the roux, add sliced sausage, and simmer over medium-low heat until vegetables are tender, 10 to 15 minutes. Remove from heat and set aside.

- Water | 3 quarts | 
- Better Than Bouillon | 2 tbsp | 
- White Sugar | 1 tablespoon | 
- Salt | To taste | 
- Hot Pepper Sauce | 2 tablespoons | 
- Cajun Seasoning | 1/2 teaspoon | 
- Bay Leaves | 4 | 
- Dried Thyme Leaves | 1/2 teaspoon | 
- Stewed Tomatoes | 14.5 ounce can | 
- Tomato Sauce | 6 ounce can | 

Combine water and Better Than Bouillon (beef flavor) in a large Dutch oven or soup pot, bring to a boil, then whisk roux mixture into the boiling water. Add sugar, salt, hot pepper sauce, Cajun seasoning, bay leaves, thyme, stewed tomatoes, and tomato sauce. Simmer over low heat for 1 hour.

- Bacon Drippings | 2 tablespoons | 
- Cut Okra | 20 ounces | 
- Distilled White Vinegar | 2 tablespoons | 

Melt bacon drippings in a skillet, add okra and vinegar, cook for 15 minutes, then remove okra with a slotted spoon and stir into the simmering gumbo.

Add shrimp and seasonings.

- Medium Shrimp | 3 pounds | 
- Worcestershire Sauce | 2 tablespoons | 

Mix in shrimp and Worcestershire sauce, and simmer until flavors have blended, 45 more minutes.

- File Powder | 4 teaspoons | 

Serve the gumbo hot, allowing each person to adjust the thickness with file powder if desired, and enjoy a taste of New Orleans.
